S'  We demonstrate gold coated polymer surface enhanced Raman scattering (SERS)\nsubstrates with a pair of complementary structures--positive and inverted\npyramids array structures fabricated by multiple-step molding and replication\nprocess. The uniform SERS enhancement factors over the entire device surfaces\nwere measured as 7.2 X 10^4 for positive pyramids substrate while 1.6 X 10^6\nfor inverted pyramids substrate with Rhodamine 6G as the target analyte. Based\non the optical reflection measurement and FDTD simulation result, the\nenhancement factor difference is attributed to plasmon resonance matching and\nto SERS "hot spots ". With this simple, fast and versatile complementary\nmolding process, we can produce polymer SERS substrates with extremely low\ncost, high throughput and high repeatability.\n'
